{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_amaryllis_ver01/data/sn83007243/00414210247/1958050201/0514.xml":{"full_text":"ifll!\nHoliness Pope Pius Xll. is\none of the illustrious person\nalities who have spoken theft.\nThe Pope addressed an over\nflow luncheon at the club on\nOctober 22. 1936. when as\nEugenia Cardinal Pacelli,\nSecretary of State, he visited\nthis country.\nIntroduced by club presi\nV rftnt George W. Stimpson as\ndistinguished diplomat, a\nscholar and a great church\nman,\" the Cardinal teld the\nmore than 400 newspapermen\nthat the address he was mak\nfng to them was \"the only ex\neeption which I have made in\nmy plans for a private and\ny personal visit to this great\nand powerful nation.\"\nThe Catholic Church and\nthe Holy Father (Pope Pius\nXI) \"desire greatly the pro\nteetion of the peace\u2014social\npeace and peace among the\n\u20225, nations,\" the then Cardinal\nPacelli told the gathering.\nHe also told the newsmen that\n\"His Holiness appeals to you\nwho have great responsibil\nity in reporting facts and in\ninspiring public opinion\" to\nlabor \"for the salvation of\nhumanity and to elevate it to\nward its greatest, its highest\ndestiny.\"\nup\njob. You\nwill never see Christ or\nChristians in Sacred\nScripture approving birth con\ntrol.\nMahatma Gandhi'g comment\non this practice, as a means\nof reducing population, is a\nforceful one: \"It lis reserved\nfor our generation,\" he says,\n\"to glorify vice by calling it\n\u2022irtue.\"\nAs a previa* of what if or\ntould happen elsewhere, tat\nus see what birth control is\ndoing to Japan. Since birth\ncontrol has been legalized in\nJapan, the United Nations re\nports that there is one abor\ntion for every live birth.\nThe Japanese see no dif\nference between mechanical\ndevices to control birth rates\nand abortion.\nThey arc logical in prin\ncipal It is estimated that two\nthirds of their birth control\nia by abortion, one-third by\ncontraceptives. They have\nover 2,000,000 abortions a\nyear.\nThey admit having killed\n11,000.000 children since this\nlaw was passed in 1948 and\nover one quarter million of\nthe people have been ster\nilized.\nMany of the thinkers there\naay that now the people re\nsemble cattle. They have lost\ntheir inner drives, their pur\nin life, their will to live.\nThere is sheer physical in\u00ad\n('The charge is some\ntimes made that the\nCatholic social action\nmovement in the United\nStates has tended to\nor\n{iturgy\ny W-*T\nr-\nSjl\u2014The Catholic Times Friday, May 2, 1958\nThe Washington Letter\nS WASHINGTON \u2014The\nNational Press Club in\nthis city is currently ob\nserving its 50th anniver\nsary, recalling that the\npresent Holy Father, His\nPope Once Spoke At\nWashington News Club\nMaking Marriage Click\nIf it is only a matter\nof getting rid of people,\nthen birth control is do\ning a bang\nHe invited those present to\njoin in the Holy Father's dUily\nprayer for the peace and pros\nperity of the world.\nOne of those who helped to\narrange for Cardinal Pacelli\nto speak at the National Press\nClub was one of the club's\nbest known members, Frank\nA. Hall, director of the N. C.\nW. C. News Service\nFollowing the Cardinal's ad\ndress., club officers escorted\nhim to the elevator on the\n13th floor of the large down\ntown building, saw him down\nto the ground floor and out\nto his car waiting at the 14th\nstreet entrance.\nAfter he had entered his\ncar, the Cardinal called Mr.\nHall to a window and asked\nin a spirit almost of humility,\nif iMr. Hall thought he had\ndone well on the visit.\nMr. Hall had no doubts\nabout that at all. and so as\nsured the Cardinal with en\nthusiasm, for he had seen\nthat the club auditorium was\nmore jammed that it had ever\nbeen in its history, that the\nstanding ovation after the\nCardinal spoke was unprece\ndented and that he had heard\nnothing but enthusiastic praise\nafterwards.\nThe visit of the Cardinal,\nnow Pope, is fresh in the mem*\nory of countless club members\neven today.\nA brilliant banquet just\nheld has so far been the\nhighlight of the golden jubi\nlee observance. It attracted\nBirth Control Gets Rid\nOf People Wot Problems\nBy Msgr. Irving A. DcBlauc\ndulgence, the avoidance of re\ns o n s i i i y a w e a k e n e\nstamina. And Japan is the\ngateway to all Asia!\nThe practice of birth control\nwill spread. In communist\nYugoslavia, Dr. Abraham\nStone reports that there are\nalready more abortions than\nlive births. If men can arbi\ntrarily control the life of un\nwanted children by birth con\ntrol, will they not \"logically\"\nwant to control the life of a\nwiJe by \"wife control!\" This\nstruggle against too many\ning beings is becoming ft\nstruggle against life itself.\nThe dominant emotion is\nfear the prevailing thought\nis a lack of confidence in the\nfuture. Unnatural birth con\ntrof and sterilization are ded\nicated to defeatism and self\nishness.\nWhat a way of life!\nShall we safeguard the priv\nileges of rich nations and\nignore those of poor nations?\nWhat a picture we must pre\nsent to the Moslems and non\nChristian Asiatics whom we\nhope to convert to Catholic\nism!\nAnd they have been taught\nto see in us a Christian civil\nization!\nThis'is birth control from\nthe moral viewpoint. Will it\nalone be the answer from the\nsociological viewpoint?\nIn Japan, for instance, tho\nlabor force for the next IS\nor 20 years hat already been\nborn. Almost 1,000,000 new\njobs will have to be created\nevery year in order to meet\nThe Yardstick\nov\u00ad\neremphasize purely nat\nural\nmaterial\nmeasures of\n\u2022ocial reform, to the neglect\nthe spiritual and supernat\nural.\nThe late Father Virgil Mich\n\u20221, O.S.B., whose biography\nwas reviewed and highly rec\nommended in this column on\nJune 24, 1957, was one of\nthose who felt most strongly\n\u2022bout this matter. Father\nMichel was particularly crit\nical of the social action move\nment for failing to build its\n\u2022rogram around the Church's\nwhich, he insisted, is\n,tfce indispensable basis of an\nadequate program of Chris-\nHon social reconstruction.\nAssuming that this is a valid\ncriticism, I would ascribe the\ndifficulty, at least in part, to\nthe relative scarcity of good\nbooks and pamphlets in the\nEnglish language on the social\nimplications of theology and\n\u00abn the relationship between\nliturgy and social action.\nUntil recently, for example,#\n\\\u00abV\u00abven our catechisms (I am re\nferring here to unofficial cat\n#chi\u00bbrrs written especially\nadult*) few iaikn abort\nA\nAids\nilCW DOOK\nof the mark in this regat^jL\nMost of those with which\nam familiar tend to present\nCatholic theology in a rather\npiecemeal fashion and more or\nleas in a vacuum, with little\nor no attempt even to sug\ngest. much less develop, its\nimplications in the field of so\ncial\nand economic reform.\nNEW CATECHISM\nIt is encouraging to note,\nhowever, that this defect is\ngradually being remedied.\nWe now have a number of\npublications in our own lan\nguage\u2014books, pamphlets and\nperiodicals\u2014which will make\nit easier for the average\nCatholic to understand the re\nlationship between theology\nand everyday living and to\nsee the intimate connection\nbetween the liturgical move\nment and the social action\nmovement.\nOne of the best of these\npublications is a new cate\nchism for adults entitled\n\"Life In Christ,\" which will\nbe ready for distribution on\nJune 1 (Life In Christ Pub\nlishers. 720 North Rush\nStreet. Chicago 11, Dl., $1.00,\npaper-bound).\nThis n\u00bbw catachlam is tho\nwork of two Chicago priests,\nPr. Jamas KilgalUn atnd Fr.\nftlfiril D_ U/.L... mka-kld thl wall AS tha\n1\nn i\nmore than 1,000 persons, in*\neluding Chief Justice War?\nren. Secretary of State Dulles,\nformer President Truman and\nnumerous other leaders in\ngovernment and the diplomat,\nic corps.\nHeading e o i e e\nwhich put long months into\nplanning the dinner was John\nC. O'Brien, a former club\npresident, Washington corres\npondent of the Philadelphia\nInquirer and a columnist for\nnumerous Catholic newspaper!\nthroughout the United States.\nA feature of the banquet\nprogram was the reproduc\ntion of signatures of a scort\nof dignitaries, from amongf\nthe many, that appear in the\nguest book of the club.\nThey include E. Card, Pat*\n\u2022lli, Theodore Roosevelt,\nWoodrow Wilson, (Marshal) F.\nFoch, Franklin D. Roosevelt,\n{(Marshal) J. Joffre, William\nH. Taft, John J. Pershing,\nDwight D. Eisenhower, Calf\nvin Coolidge and Harry\nTruman.\nThe National Press Club is\nperhaps the largest and best\nknown organization of news\npapermen in the world. It has\na total of more than 4,600\nmembers. Of these approxi\nmately 1,000 are active mem\nbers, and more than 2,000 are\nnon-resident members. Of the\nremainder, more than 800 are\nnon-active members and more\nthan 700 are associate mem\nbers.\nthe demands of the maturing\nchildren already in existence.\nThe real core of the problem\nis not how many children must\nbe nourished, but how many\njobs can be created.\nIn 1955, for instance, there\nwere 714.869 marriages and\n693,098 deaths.\nUv*\nJapan must import very\nmuch of its wood, petroleum,\nsalt, tin, aluminum, anti\nmony,'and so on. \"No amount\nof family planning,\" says\nFather Anthony Zimmerman,\nS.V.D. in his monumental\nbook, Overpopulation, can\nbring these vital necessities\nto Japan.\" Birth control is\nmuch leas tha answer than\ntrade, international coopera\ntion, human solidarity, and\nan all out effort on the part\nof the countries with capital,\ntrained technicians, and Chris\ntian principles.\nFWT T) 1 A 1 s which his physician has been un- a I\nlntCffratlOll 1\nOf Liturgy and Social Action 1^ riS^sT the^:\nBy Msgr. George G. Higgins\nBy LEO TRESE\nRecently\nwe\nsons who have suffered\nsome form of emotional\nor\nStatistics give little rodm\nfor hope that Japan's popula\ntion can actually begin to de\ncrease for decades and dec\nades. And when that does\ncome about in a foreseeable\nfuture there will be other\nproblems.\nSince.\nPeople such as these, who rec\nognize nervous disorders for\nwhat they are and have the de\nsire to do something about\nthem, arc the fortunate ones.\nhas\nIf every married couple in\nJapan were allowed only one\nchild during its entire mar\nried life, it is again to court\ndisaster, for in the future two\nchildren might have to sup\nport four aging parents and\ntheir own offspring besides.\nUnder population in the labor\nforce would then prove a\nworse tragedy than overpopu\nlation.\na\nA dozen doctors\nthat there\nfor his heart palpitations,\nHe still thinks the doctors\nhidden physical cause.\n)n\nori\u00ael.n*\nphosphate, potash, iron, lead, tally mistaken, of course) that\nthere is something shameful\nabout trouble \"all in the mind.\nab,e\nprofessional counsal and as\nsistanca of a team of experts\nin dogmatic thaology, biblical\nstudias, tha lay apostolata, and\nCatholic social action.\nThe authors hope that tho\nbook will solve a problem\nwhich plagues many priests\nin their work of instructing\nconverts\u2014that of providing\na text which is acceptable to\na person with a high school\nor college education one\nwhich is Christo-centric\none which emphasizes the\ndoctrines of the divine life\nof grace and the Mystical\nBody and gives due promin\nence to the liturgy an\u00a3 the\nlay apostolate.\nThe new catechism gelies\nheavily on the Sacred Scrip\ntures in its pedagogical meth\nod. In fact, a fully effective\nuse of the book requires, as\nthe introduction states, a cer\ntain amount of Scripture read\ning concomitant with the lea\nsons.\nEach lesson is introduced by\na rather' extended passage\nfrom Scripture and an explan\natory paragraph which pre\npares the reader for the ques\ntions which follow.\nAt the end of each lesson a\npractice is suggested in an ef\nfort. to engage the will as\nr\\f\nh\",v if*\ndscussed\nmental health That has\nbrought letters from per-\nHe thinks that to do so would richer life.\nI 'hItTiu,v.eisn\" syo.being\nto find any organic cause,\nthere is a remarkably effective\nreader in the course of the ill*\nstructions.\nDevotional practices and\nprayers are introduced grad*\nually in connection with the,\nunderlying doctrines, as is1 the\nre-living of the life of Christ\nthrough the liturgical year.\nOne entire chapter of the\ncatechism is devoted to a sum*\nmary, in practical terms, of\nthe essentials of Catholic so\ncial teaching.\nThis new catechism by\nFathers Killgallon and Weber\nis one of the best works of\nits kind I havfe ever come\nacross. While it is intended\nprimarily for the instruction\nof prospective converts to the\nFaith, it can also be recom\nmended very highly to cradle\nCatholics.\nIndeed, if I were conducting\na labor school or any other\ntype of social action program\nat the local level, 1 think I\nwould make it required read\ning for all tl\\e Catholic stu\ndents.\nI don't know of apy other\nshort book in the English\nlanguage which so successful\nly presents Catholic theology\nas a unified whole and so ef\nfectively develops the impli\ncations of this theology\nin\nterms of everyday living.\nSuffice it to say that it'll\nthe sort of book that un\ndoubtedly would gladden tho\ntha K\u00bbrl nf tho lata Virtnl Mich\u00bbl\n1\n*7\nThe Way to Peace\nm*ny\nToo often the person with an\ndicap will cling stubbornly to another\nthe\nphysical cause. the guidance of a trained leader\nmay tell him\nis\nor re-techniques.\naamtiiM\u00abmw\ni\nRecovery Inc. Aids Those\nWith Nervous Disorders\nhelp path to mental health call- be persons who\nit is about 20 years since Re-\ncoverv was started by\nor extreme fatigue or trembling, are amazed to discover that so they are welcome to share a\nor depression, or over-anxiety.' many others share their prob- bodk with someone else. I\nare\nlems-\nwin\nwrong still thinks there is a Members of a Recovery group is listed in the telephone book. I Yet,\nnow jn ftecoveIT maintain the t0\n-a .u\u00b0r mental 