r psycho- Recovery phone number is list\nThis is the person really to logical illness which easily could ed. may obtain information by\nbe pitied, because it is next to jjave ]e(j hospitalization if Re- writing to Recovery, Inc., 116 S\nimpossible to persuade him to\nCovery\nseek the kind of help he needs, needed therapy. For anyone with a nervous ill\nHe will recoil almost in horror others, with lesser prob- ness, a phone call or letter may\nfrom the thought of consulting Jems, find in Recovery the aids be the first step toward health\na psychiatrist. which help them to a happier, and happiness. In Columbus,\nhad not provided the Michigan Ave., Chicago 3, 111\nmoro\nChristlika to aim for tha ro\u00ab\nhabilitation of criminals rath\n\u2022r than to axacuto tham as\n*w\u00bb do now? What is tha posi.\ntisn of tha Church in regard\nto capital punishment?\nA. Christian teaching hat\nalways insisted upon the dig\nnity and importance of every\nman and the power of God's\ngrace to enable him to change,\nno matter how terrible he may\nappear to be (e.g. the thief on\nthe cross). It would seem to\nbe Christlike to do everything\npossible to help convicted\ncriminals develop their tal\nents for positive and con\nstructive work and most mod\nern sociologists agree with\nthis aim. The arguments for\ncapital punishment are not\nnecessarily weakened by this\nline of reasoning, for few so\ncieties as complex as ours\nhave been able to avoid ex\ntreme crimes (i.e. to limit\ntheir ocurrence) without cap\nital punishment. If it could be\nproved that the most terriblo\ncrimes would be no more\ncommon than they are now\nthere would seem to be no\nreason to keep capital punish,\nment. The Catholic Church\ndoes not advocate capital pun\nishment it does not condemn\nits use when it is judged nec\nessary for punishing and pre\nventing major serious crimes.\nQ. If a man takes his lifo\nby suicido is he refused Chris\ntian burial? What are lilt\nchances of saving his soul?\n,.A\u00ab SwfrffiP axe to bfi iar-,\nRecovery, inc.,\ninclude per s o n s who A call will bring the information |ish\nHe cannot bear to admit that \"7, to say the very least- indifferent to all religion, and\nwith nervous disorders snd who ^o dpplicdtion li needed I 11 01\nhis infirmity may be nervous\nRecover}', Box\nFinally, some members may Station.\nWhat's Church Position\n3544,\nGarden Of Eden:\nsuch illnesses, and the remedies. This is a thoroughly Christian lcltt r, 4., 1 ..t,,.!. i_\u201e\nThey share their experiences concept, even though Recovery\nImonks decided that the Catholic schools\u2014Iby far the\nwill find the spiritual help\nhe\nneeds in his own church and\nfee\ncurrent headaches, or attacks of Beginners Recovery, who erv group. Members are asked\nBeechwold\nbidden Christian buriaL In\npractice, however, the Church\nrecognizes that for varioua\nreasons a person may not be\nguilty of the sufficient reflec\ntion and full consent of tho\nwill required to constitute the\ngin of suicide. In many cases\nwhere the person has been a\ngood Catholic it is obvious\nthat his action was not char\nacteristic and the pastor (often\nafter consultation with the\nbishop) may permit Christian\nburial. Only God knows the\nfate of a person's soul and\nsuch a person could be guilty\nof no sin (or at least no ser\nious sin) in his desperate ac\ntion or could make an act of\nperfection contrition for any\nsin he had. St. John Vianney,\nthe Cure of Ars, is reported to\nhave told the unhappy wife of\na suicide that the man had\nmade an act of perfect contri\ntion between the bridge (from\nwhich he leaped) and the\nground.\nQ. Can the Poor Souls in\nPurgatory know when we pray\nfor thom and have Masses of\nfered for them?\nA. It is commonly thought\nthat the souls in purgatory\ncan help us, since they are\npart of the Communion of\nSaints even in the time of\ntheir purgation. St. Robert\nBellarmine, St. Alphonsus and\nothers hold that it is possible\nfor us to gain their inter\ncession. That would seem to\nindicate that they can have\nawareness of us and there is\nno reason tQ doubt t-hat thev\np-S j- s\nSoviets Are Making\nHeadway In Ceylon\nItradition.\"\n|an(j\nfound ft\nfor participation in a Recov- Buddhist,\nBy Erik v. Kuehnelt-Leddihn\nfor-*'long time, especially during Mid\nlAges, the notion prevailed that the Garden of Eden\nhad perhaps not been in Mesopotamia, but in Ceylon.\nSituated not far north from the Equator this is\n|deed an island of great natural beauty.\nIt was a British Colony until after the war, then\nlit .became a free member of the Commonwealth, but\nsince the last elections, about 19 months ago, the shad\nows of Moscow have been lengthening over the fair\nisle.\nAgain this is a country with a partly Catholic\nhistory. Soon after I landed I wandered through\n(churches, rectories, Catholic bookstores, seminaries,\nand schools. I was most painfully aware of the fact\nthat we Catholios are \"citizens\" of a truly Celestial\nCity, members of a Mystical Body, but how few\namong us have even a remote idea how worldwide\nour Church is, what forms she assumes throughout\nthe globe, what sufferings she has to go through#\nwhat problems to face.\nI am sure if I write the words \"The Church In\nCeylon,\" it will hardly, ring a bell in the minds of\nany of mf readers. It does now in mine now that\nI have seen from a plane Adam's Peak and Adam's\nBridge, now that I have strolled through the streets\nof Colombo and Kandy.\nThe Faith spread in Colombo immediately after\nthe arrival of the Portuguese\u2014Asia's Catholic salt\nin the 16th century. In their gentle and persuasive\nway Portuguese missionaries and laymen converted\na number of the local inhabitants, Sinhalese and\nTamils who had come over from India.\nThen the Dutch came and conquered Ceylon\nwhile the Portuguese motherland came under Span\nish rule and was powerless to protect the faithful.\nI The Catholic Church was outlawed and Catholics\nwere persecuted. Then, from India came an Indian\nloratorian, Father Vaz, disguised and working \"under\nground\" to keep the newly planted Faith alive.\nThe Dutch and the subsequent British rule was\nnever able to exterminate the Catholic religion.\nAs a matter of fact, many of the Dutch descendants,\nIthe co-called \"Burghers\" intermarried with the\n(Portuguese and embraced the Catholic Faith.\nIn spite of their growth in numbers and\nwonderful piety and loyalty to the Church the Cath\nolics are only a minority in Ceylon\u2014even if a highly\nrespected one. Their schools are matchless and they\nare eagerly sought after for positions of trust and\nresponsibility.\nThe majority,- though, is still composed of\n(Buddhists and some Hinduists. And since independent\nICeylon is a democracy, which means free and\n[elections, the Catholics, naturally, cannot make them-\nfelt politically\nAs a matter of fact, they can and actually did be\ncome the target of a common Buddhist-Leftist-Na\ntionalist front. The old principle again prevailedif\nneed be, the enemies of the Church will always entQr\na coalition to fight the Rock, to fight the Church.\nAnd this even happened in Ceylon, that Garden of\nEden, full of the most beautiful flowers and birds,\nthe land of elephants, gorgeous temple, and butter\nflies.\nCeylon's first independent government was\n1\nlevelheaded. Then the Buddhists priests and\nbest in the country\u2014were a menace to tne national\nmem- I Trying to cover up their own weakness, their\n[own low scholastic standards, and their lack of vo-\n|cations, they were looking for an enemy elsewhere\njn the\nCatholic\na Mr.\nI\"\nlly supported Mr. Banaaranaike s\nwon the elections and which now\nI process\nof nationalization.\nsince\nMr. Bandaranaike\nattend. Recov\u00abry meeting, speculations of the Buddhists went awry.\nI Still, the present government, which has na-\nItionalized all means of transportation, now wants to\n\"nationalize\" (which means to steal the non-public\nschools and hospitals.\nAdded to this are the intimate ties'with the Soviet\nUnion and the \"People's Democracies.\" When I arrived\nin Colombo a huge Soviet delegation stayed in the\nswank Galle Face Hotel.\nWhen I checked in at the Queen's Hotel in Kandy\nI stumbled upon a Rumanian Cultural delegation\nIconsisting of 48 heads. All these are ominous signs\nfor those who can read them.\ncan know of our prayers for\nthem. It would seem likely\n(that God would let them know,\n1 at least after their entry into\nheaven, of the souls who\nhelped them. It is a matter of\nCatholic Faith that we can\"\nhelp the souls in purgatory\nby prayers, good works and\nthe Holy Sacrifice of the Mass\noffered for them.\nQ, Doesn't the Church rut*\nout tha possibility of astrology,\nbeing of some value too quick\nly? Couldn't we be affected\nby the astral radiations or\nsomething of that sort at tho\ntime of our birth?\nA. The Catholic Church for\nI bids placing confidence in\nconsultation with astrologers\nor their literature because be\nlief in their predictions is\nsuperstition, forbidden by the\nFirst Commandment. While it\nis remotely possible that the\nheavenly bodies have some\neffect upon us it is supersti\ntious to attribute to their posi\ntion at the time of our birth\n5\n,\u00bbJ\nAi\nsecret\nChurch. (Only recently\nFonseka, cried\nout that if the\nnation\nr}ll1v thp\nwill fall a\norev to\nlettist\nparty wmcn\nIS\nhellbent upon ft\n(a graduate\nUniversitv where he got his socialist views) is\u2014\nof\na Brit-\n(or any other time) and ser\nious influence on our future\nor our character. We are in\nfluenced by the weather but\n,not compelled to any particu\nlar course of action thereby.\nQ. When can a priest ad\nminister the sacrament\nConfirmation?\nA. In 1947 pastors every\nwhere were given the author\nization to act as extraordin\nary ministers of the sacra\nment. This power may be\nused only by the pastor and\nonly for those within the par\nish who are in danger of death\n(sickness, accident or old\nage). While the sacrament is\ndirected toward apostolic ac\ntion it is one which imprints\na permanent character upon\nthe soul and the Church wish\nes every person to have the\ngraces and the eternal char\nacter of confirmed Christians.\nSend questions to Father\nEdward F. Healey, Inquiry\nCorner, The Catholic Times,\nBox 636, Columbus (16) Ohio.\nTHE CATHOLIC TIMES\npublished Every Week by\nThe Catholic Times, Inc.\nColumbus, Ohio\nHIOTICE: Send All Change of Address t*\nP.O. Box 636 Columbus, Ohio\nExecutive and Editorial Offices: 1?\n1(46 E. Town Street, Columbus 15, Ohio\nAddress all communications for publication\nto P. O. Box 636, Columbus 16, Ohio\nCopy Deadline is noon, Saturday before Publication Dit#\nTelephones: CA. 4-5195 CA. 4-5196\nPrice of The CathoUc Times is S3 per year. All subscriptieae\nshould be presented to our ofln through the pastors of the pa^\nishes.\nRemittances should be made payable to The Catholic Times.\nAnonymous communications will be disregarded.\nWe do not hold ourselves responsible for any views or opin\nion* expressed in the communications of our correspondents.\nEntered as Second Class Matter at Post Office, Columbus, Ohio.\nSt Francis de Sales, Patron of the Catholic Press. Pray for nai\nTHIS NEWSPAPER PRINTED BY UNION LABOR\nil\n2f\nv\"\n.yi","height":"29151","width":"19401"}}
